In article <30rq75$pbt@rzsun02.rrz.uni-hamburg.de>, bontchev@rzddec2.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev) writes:
|> Jason W Solinsky (solman@athena.mit.edu) writes:
|> 
|> > Well here a stronger claim: If you use a two known secure ciphers back to
|> > back, and these two ciphers are unrelated to each other, there is a ZERO
|> > percent chance that they will decrease your security. And they add quite a
|> 
|> Could you prove this claim or provide a reference to a work where it
|> is proven?

Its part of the definition of security. Application of a secure cypher can
not decrease the entropy of the input plaintext. Therefore, if the two cyphers
are unrelated, the resultant cyphertext will not be more easily decrypted.

JWS
